<subSubSection pageId="184" pageNumber="185" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
Perennial herb from a woody base, stems prostrate, reaching 50 cm, the whole plant densely villous. Leaves sessile, 2-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.4-1.3 cm, oblanceolate or oblong, becoming elliptic upwards, obtuse, margin entire, lower leaves attenuate at base, upper leaves and bracts cuneate, veins prominent, internodes short so leaves and flower heads more crowded than in related species. Inflorescence characteristically narrow, flowers 1-5 in subsessile, congested head-like scorpioid cymes; peduncle 0-1.5 cm; bracteoles 8-11 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-5 mm, lanceolate to ovate, acute; pedicels absent; outer sepals 12-15 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-4 mm, oblong, acuminate, flat; middle sepal asymmetric; inner sepals slightly shorter and narrower; corolla 2-2.8 cm long, usually creamy with a yellowish centre, weakly lobed, midpetaline bands long-sericeous; ovary and style glabrous, style divided 6 mm above base, stigmas 3mm; capsule glabrous, 1-seeded (fide 
<bibRefCitation author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
); seeds glabrous. [
<bibRefCitation author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
: 168; 
<bibRefCitation author="Tohme, G" journalOrPublisher="National Council for Scientific Research, Beirut" pageId="213" pageNumber="214" pagination="1 - 609" refId="B363" refString="Tohme, G, Tohme, H, 2007. Illustrated Flora of Lebanon. National Council for Scientific Research, Beirut: 1 - 609" title="Illustrated Flora of Lebanon" year="2007">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tohmé">Tohme</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tohmé">Tohme</normalizedToken>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
: 216 (photo)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="184" pageNumber="185" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
Turkey (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Uslu</emphasis>
1363, 2671); Syria (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Aucher-Eloy</emphasis>
1398); Lebanon (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Gombault</emphasis>
693, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Blanche</emphasis>
1457); Palestine/Israel (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Eig &amp; Grizzi</emphasis>
369, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bornmüller">Bornmueller</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
1108, 1109; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Meyers &amp; Dinsmore</emphasis>
272; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Davis</emphasis>
4424, 4672). On coastal sand. Records from Egypt are probably errors.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="184" pageNumber="185" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
Unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vahl, Symb. Bot. 1: 16. 1790. (Vahl" authorityYear="1790" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus lanatus" order="Solanales" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Convolvulus lanatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
this species appears to have long trailing stems, which may become somewhat woody when old, but it lacks the spinescent basal branches of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vahl, Symb. Bot. 1: 16. 1790. (Vahl" authorityYear="1790" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus lanatus" order="Solanales" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Convolvulus lanatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The sepals are also more shortly villous so the heads are more or less separate. It differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boiss., Diagn. Pl. Orient. 11: 81. 1849. (Boissier" authorityYear="1849" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus schimperi" order="Solanales" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schimperi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Convolvulus schimperi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the subsessile heads and leaves not undulate-margined and from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peter ex Hallier f., Bot. Jahrb. Syst. 18: 99. 1893 [&quot; 1894 &quot;]. (Hallier" authorityYear="1893" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus spicatus" order="Solanales" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spicatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Convolvulus spicatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the subsessile heads although short peduncles are clearly present in some specimens such as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Melville</emphasis>
70/31 and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Samuelson</emphasis>
527 (both K).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
Species 178-181 are extremely similar and may prove to be conspecific. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus cephalodus" order="Solanales" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cephalodus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Convolvulus cephalodus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the hirsute ovary, but other distinctions are essentially minor differences of leaf shape. Clearly further collections are needed but not even the ovary indumentum is very convincing in the absence of other distinguishing characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
